<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-12-08T19:23:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-12-08T19:23:00-05:00" n="296" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d296">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">320/12–850: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The United States Representative at the United
                                    Nations</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Austin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-12-08T19:23:00-05:00">December 8, 1950—7:23 p. m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 392.… South West Africa.
                                Delegation reviewed position US should take in plenary. It was
                                agreed we should seek defeat resolution recommended by Committee 4
                                    (US/<gloss target="#t_A1">A</gloss>/C.4/201) and offer
                                substitute resolution (US/<gloss target="#t_A1">A</gloss>/C.4/202).<note n="1" xml:id="d296fn1">For Doc.
                                        US/<gloss target="#t_A1">A</gloss>/C.4/201, see <ref target="#pg_503">p. 503</ref>. Doc. US/<gloss target="#t_A1">A</gloss>/C.4/202 is not printed; for the later and final
                                    text of the substitute resolution, see <ref target="#pg_507">p.
                                        507</ref>.</note> Point was made Union would like nothing
                                better than adoption Committee 4 resolution which would give it
                                excuse to do nothing, whereas substitute resolution gave promise of
                                concrete results and appeared to have reasonable chance of obtaining
                                required two-thirds majority following defeat of committee
                                resolution.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Austin</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>